**Steps to Reproduce**:

Use the following code:
```cs
using ExtensionsExample.Base;

namespace ExtensionsExample.Base
{
    public static class FluentExtensions
    {
        extension<T>(IEnumerable<T> enumerable)
        {
            public bool Any => enumerable.Any();
        }
    }
}

namespace ExtensionsExample.Another
{
    public static class Repro
    {
        public static void Something(object[] source)
        {
            var any = source.Any;
        }

        public static void Something<T>(IEnumerable<T> source)
        {
            var any = source.Any;
        }
    }
}
```

Observe that the `source.Any` expressions in both the collection types will cause an error.

It is important that the extension be defined in a namespace that is only accessible to the usage via a using. If we used the extension in a subnamespace like `ExtensionsExample.Base.More`, the extension would correctly be used.

**Expected Behavior**:
No error; the `Any` should bind to the extension property, since it's not invoked. If it were invoked, it should bind to the method

**Actual Behavior**:
Error [CS9286](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/assembly-references?f1url=%3FappId%3Droslyn%26k%3Dk(CS9286)#missing-references)
'object[]' does not contain a definition for 'Any' and no accessible extension member 'Any' for receiver of type 'object[]' could be found (are you missing a using directive or an assembly reference?)

**Note**:
This is a complex scenario where the compiler must disambiguate two extensions, one property and one method, which property could be invokable much like the disambiguated method. It might not have been specced that the disambiguation will prefer methods over properties depending on whether the expression is being invoked or not.
